### 6. IVY Hackathon Report
Nigel Davis presented the results of the IVY hackathon using the presentation [IVY hackathon](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-ivy-ivy-hackathon-00).

* **Hackathon Highlights:**
  * Focused on evaluating the compatibility of IVY and TAPI models and demonstrating interoperability using actual products from Cisco and Ciena.
  * Successfully demonstrated the propagation of data and mappings between TAPI and IVY models.
* **Technical Findings:**
  * Both TAPI and IVY provide a strong equipment representation.
  * Functional designations (such as ROADM or OTN switch) are intentionally excluded from both models. Instead, capabilities should be used to dynamically determine what a component can do.
  * Successfully mapped "holder embedded in equipment", which is handled differently in TAPI than in IVY.
* **Discussion:**
  * Italo Busi agreed with omitting explicit functional types since devices are highly versatile and can mutate, but suggested adding examples in the draft to clarify this rationale for operators.
  * Camillo Cardona and Roberto Manzotti pointed out that Network Operation Centers (NOCs) value simple functional descriptions for user experience (UX). Nigel Davis suggested this could be handled at the UI layer by interpreting capability properties.
  * Victor Lopez inquired about extending hackathon test cases to IP-side validation and using streaming/notifications (such as YANG Push). Nigel Davis welcomed this direction for future hackathons.

